It's become my way to--.

00:53:49.400 --> 00:53:50.400
Like I hear about someone think they're cool.

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:51.400
I can touch base with them by doing the comic.

00:53:51.400 --> 00:53:52.400
It's like, everyone like to be drawn.

00:53:52.400 --> 00:53:53.400
And I haven't gotten Neil deGrasse Tyson . And
I've done two comics about him.

00:53:53.400 --> 00:53:54.400
And he won't get in touch with me.

00:53:54.400 --> 00:53:55.400
We should be best friends.

00:53:55.400 --> 00:53:56.400
[laughter]

00:53:56.400 --> 00:53:57.400
It's been nice.

00:53:57.400 --> 00:53:58.400
I've had times when I--.

00:53:58.400 --> 00:53:59.400
Well, Kip Thorne is the best example.

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:00.400
I've had other professors I've met just through
the comics and I could be like, "I was having

00:54:00.400 --> 00:54:01.400
trouble with my physics homework and could
you help me with this?"

00:54:01.400 --> 00:54:02.400
[laughter]

00:54:02.400 --> 00:54:03.400
I actually did that once.

00:54:03.400 --> 00:54:04.400
A friend of mine, Sean Carroll, he wrote a
book called "From Eternity to Here," and he

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:05.400
does a blog called Cosmic Variance.

00:54:05.400 --> 00:54:06.400
And when I was just first learning physics,
he was a fan of the comic and we--.

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:07.400
Now when I have a problem--.

00:54:07.400 --> 00:54:08.400
I would never ask him like, "Solve this equation
for me."

00:54:08.400 --> 00:54:09.400
'Cause he's a professor at Caltech.

00:54:09.400 --> 00:54:10.400
That might be rude.

00:54:10.400 --> 00:54:11.400
[laughter]

00:54:11.400 --> 00:54:12.400
But I would be like, "I really can't understand
this concept.

00:54:12.400 --> 00:54:13.400
Could you help me with it?"

00:54:13.400 --> 00:54:14.400
He was actually really nice.

00:54:14.400 --> 00:54:15.400
He would write paragraphs to me.

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:16.400
It was really cool.

00:54:16.400 --> 00:54:17.400
And so, that's the really nice, unexpected
side effects of doing cartoons.

00:54:17.400 --> 00:54:18.400
And what's really cool, too, similarly, is
I'm learning something in math and I have

00:54:18.400 --> 00:54:19.400
trouble with a definition or a problem or
something, I'll push it on Twitter and I will

00:54:19.400 --> 00:54:20.400
get 18 answers in ten seconds.

00:54:20.400 --> 00:54:21.400
It's really amazing.

00:54:21.400 --> 00:54:22.400
&gt;&gt;MALE #31: How many of them are correct?

00:54:22.400 --> 00:54:23.400
[laughter]

00:54:23.400 --> 00:54:24.400
&gt;&gt;Zach Weinersmith: That is the problem.

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:25.400
What's more interesting is usually it's 90
percent correct.

00:54:25.400 --> 00:54:26.400
There are people who are wrong, but what's
really interesting is you will ask a question

00:54:26.400 --> 00:54:27.400
and you will say, "Why is this so?"

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:28.400
I'll give you an example I did recently.

00:54:28.400 --> 00:54:29.400
I was doing these calculus blogs and what's
nice about it is I'm figuring out all the

00:54:29.400 --> 00:54:30.400
things I never actually learned but felt like
I knew.

00:54:30.400 --> 00:54:31.400
So, as you probably remember from a long time
ago, inverse trigonometrical functions have

00:54:31.400 --> 00:54:32.400
a restricted domain.

00:54:32.400 --> 00:54:33.400
And it's very reasonable to make a restricted
domain 'cause otherwise the math doesn't work.

00:54:33.400 --> 00:54:34.400
But you suspect there must be an intuitive
reason why this might be the case.

00:54:34.400 --> 00:54:35.400
And so, I went to Twitter and I said, "Can
anyone--."

00:54:35.400 --> 00:54:36.400
Of course, I understood why you restrict the
domain for the math part.

00:54:36.400 --> 00:54:37.400
That's the obvious part.

00:54:37.400 --> 00:54:38.400
Everyone understands that instantly.

00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:39.400
But why should it be in a human intuitive
way?

00:54:39.400 --> 00:54:40.400
And so, I go to Twitter and I'm like, "Hey,
could anyone give me an insight on this?"

00:54:40.400 --> 00:54:41.400
And instantly, it was 40 people saying that
you have to restrict the domain so the math

00:54:41.400 --> 00:54:42.400
works.

00:54:42.400 --> 00:54:43.400
And I was like--.

00:54:43.400 --> 00:54:44.400
That's kind of boggling 'cause that means
most of the people who are interacting with

00:54:44.400 --> 00:54:45.400
this type of math are not even trying to have
a deeper understanding of it.

00:54:45.400 --> 00:54:46.400
But I got a couple of people who gave me other
ways to understand how it would work.

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:47.400
And actually, the best version of it I read--and
there were a couple of them--was if you imagine

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:48.400
a non-inverse trig function, it also has a
restricted range because of where it can go.

00:54:48.400 --> 00:54:49.400
So, I thought that was the best way to think
of it, is to think of inverting it.

00:54:49.400 --> 00:54:50.400
And so, it was neat to think about how--or
it was maybe scary to think about many people

00:54:50.400 --> 00:54:51.400
